[normal]Written Evidence Submitted by The Children’s Book Project for Tanzania (CBP)[bold]Executive Summery[bold]High quality education for all children including disabled in their first years of schooling builds a foundation for future learning and for healthy and productive family and civic life. 
[normal]Literacy skills equip a person to both gain knowledge and understandi
[normal]ng of their immediate environment as well as to make sense of the wider world. Research shows that a child who is able to read and write is better able to contribute to his or her personal and community well being. 
[normal]Primary Education Development Plan (PEDP
[normal] III), Big Results Now (BRN) and 
[normal]LANES
[normal] proposal firmly recognizes the importance of education to support literacy development, to ensure better lives for the Tanzanians including people with disabilities. But the cha
[normal]llenges are many including semi-
[normal]trained 
[normal]teachers for literacy, lack of Braille reading materials to read, besides having few textbooks transcribed into Braille.
[normal]The CBP
[normal]’s
[normal] experience
[normal] in Braille Book provision
[normal] is in line with the DFID
[normal]’s
[normal] missi
[normal]on to support disabled children and youths to improve th
[normal]eir lives, and prepare them to become responsible citizens 
[normal]i
[normal]n their communities.
